    {
      "id": "5874cc97f0cc85cd3aa808ed44718e9f001f4882",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 176,
        "name": "Liang Zhen",
        "email": "liang.zhen@intel.com",
        "username": "liangzhen",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2013-03-20 07:30:56.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2: I would prefer that you didn't submit this\n\n(1 inline comment)\n\n",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "266de0997510322c14f15b367372b6d059d12c3b",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2013-03-21 22:37:26.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\nIn the past we were limited to 256 niobufs (1M / 4kB), but with the large RPC size this may be quite large. The maximim number of niobufs in a request is actually PTLRPC_MAX_BRW_PAGES, assuming that we want to allow a fully fragmented IO request to be sent as a single large RPC. \n\nFrom the hard drive point of view, this is not much better than multiple separate RPCs, so it might make sense to limit the number of niobufs in a single RPC to some reasonable number like 1024. That is equal to the maximum pages in a 4MB RPC, but avoids the huge request size needed for a fragmented 32MB RPC (upwards of 128kB for the request)..",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "d60a02a3ad9edb2f21bdc7da25dc972c54053068",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 176,
        "name": "Liang Zhen",
        "email": "liang.zhen@intel.com",
        "username": "liangzhen",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2013-03-22 00:55:26.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\nAndreas, what I'm trying to ask here is about FIEMAP request size, I think that's the reason that this test failed.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "193485f2cc7ae794acd5d19601602e7cc463fce6",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2013-03-22 03:38:39.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\nOh, FIEMAP itself doesn't have a maximum size, in the same way that readdir does not. It is ok to impose some maximum request/reply size for FIEMAP. It should be at least a page I think.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "19d8b0ada090af372b9d5300d73b8736030f0042",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 176,
        "name": "Liang Zhen",
        "email": "liang.zhen@intel.com",
        "username": "liangzhen",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2013-03-22 16:15:27.000000000",
      "message": "Uploaded patch set 3.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
    },
    {
      "id": "f2614abfcc892f4a16c7a7311267ebf1831adb4c",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 176,
        "name": "Liang Zhen",
        "email": "liang.zhen@intel.com",
        "username": "liangzhen",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2013-03-22 16:42:28.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 3:\n\nI just restore the OST_MAXREQSIZE to 5K for now, which is originally enough for all requests in our tests except 4M I/O. \nWe probably should limit total number of extents in a FIEMAP request in the future, otherwise a request could be even bigger",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
    },
